Former Senator Edward Brooke, the first African-American elected as a state's Attorney General and U.S. Senator after reconstruction, has passed away. President Obama expressed his sadness and highlighted Brooke's extraordinary life of public service, including his time in the U.S. Army. Brooke was known for his role in the battle for civil rights and economic fairness, as well as his efforts to build consensus and find practical solutions to the nation's challenges. The President offered his deepest sympathies to Brooke's family and the people of Massachusetts.